05335nam a22011535i 9780691214108DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20201977nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912141087 a10.1515/97806912141082doi  a(DE-B1597)554909  a(OCoLC)1175630683  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aREL0720002bisacsh04a292.081 aKerényi, Carl, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDionysos :bArchetypal Image of Indestructible Life /cCarl Kerényi. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4c©1977  a1 online resource (608 p.) :b50 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBollingen Series (General) ;v13000tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tPREFACE -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPart One. The Cretan Prelude -- tI. MINOAN VISIONS -- tII . LIGHT AND HONEY -- tIII. THE CRETAN CORE OF THE DIONYSOS MYTH -- tPart Two. The Greek Cult and Myth -- tIV. THE MYTHS OF ARRIVAL -- tV. DIONYSOS TRIETERIKOS GOD OF THE TWO-YEAR PERIOD -- tVI. THE DIONYSOS OF THE ATHENIANS AND OF HIS WORSHIPERS IN THE GREEK MYSTERIES -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tLIST OF WORKS CITED -- tINDEX -- tC. Kerényi -- tA Bibliography of C. Kerényi0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNo other god of the Greeks is as widely present in the monuments and nature of Greece and Italy, in the sensuous tradition of antiquity, as Dionysos. In myth and image, in visionary experience and ritual representation, the Greeks possessed a complete expression of indestructible life, the essence of Dionysos. In this work, the noted mythologist and historian of religion Carl Kerényi presents a historical account of the religion of Dionysos from its beginnings in the Minoan culture down to its transition to a cosmic and cosmopolitan religion of late antiquity under the Roman Empire. From the wealth of Greek literary, epigraphic, and monumental traditions, Kerényi constructs a picture of Dionysian worship, always underlining the constitutive element of myth. Included in this study are the secret cult scenes of the women's mysteries both within and beyond Attica, the mystic sacrificial rite at Delphi, and the great public Dionysian festivals at Athens. The way in which the Athenian people received and assimilated tragedy in its immanent connection with Dionysos is seen as the greatest miracle in all cultural history. Tragedy and New Comedy are seen as high spiritual forms of the Dionysian religion, and the Dionysian element itself is seen as a chapter in the religious history of Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aRELIGION / Antiquities & Archaeology.2bisacsh  aAelian.  aAischylos.  aAlexiou.  aApollodoros.  aAthenaios.  aBeazley, J. D.  aBoeotia.  aBrindisi pitcher.  aChadwick, J.  aDelos.  aDemeter.  aDieterich.  aDiodorus Siculus.  aEileithyia.  aGerairai.  aGreat Mother.  aHerodotos.  aHesychios.  aHyginus.  aIkarios.  aJacoby.  aKallimachos.  aKern.  aKronos.  aLerna.  aMarinatos.  aMinotaur.  aNonnos.  aOnomakritos.  aOrion.  aPausanias.  aPlutarch.  aSabazios.  aStrabo.  acaves.  aenthronement.  aepidemia.  afawn.  ahanging.  alabyrinth.  amaenads.  apanthers.1 aManheim, Ralph.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691214108zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691214108423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691214108.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSI